## 16. Caching Rules

- cache RxNav normalization for 30 days
- cache openFDA / DailyMed evidence for 7 days
- retain raw upstream payloads for debugging and demo explainability
- support manual cache invalidation in case an upstream query strategy changes

Recommended cache policy:

- use database-backed cache first
- optionally add in-memory short-lived cache for hot requests

## 17. Reliability Rules

All external calls must include:

- timeout
- retry with backoff
- graceful fallback behavior
- structured error logging

### 17.1 openFDA

Documented limits:

- no key: `240 requests/minute`, `1,000/day`
- with key: `240 requests/minute`, `120,000/day`

Source:

- [openFDA authentication](https://open.fda.gov/apis/authentication/)

### 17.2 RxNav

RxNav may return `429`, and exact public limits are not fixed clearly in docs.

Therefore:

- retry with exponential backoff
- log upstream throttling separately
- avoid bursty duplicate requests by caching aggressively

### 17.3 Circuit breaker guidance

Implement lightweight circuit breaker behavior around:

- RxNav
- openFDA
- DailyMed
- OpenAI

When a dependency is unstable:

- fail fast
- return partial but honest result if possible
- surface `insufficient_evidence` instead of fabricating certainty

## 18. Observability and Debugging Requirements

This is mandatory.

Every request should have:

- `requestId`
- `traceId`
- `userId` if available
- endpoint name
- execution duration

Each external call should log:

- provider name
- request target
- lookup key
- latency
- retry count
- status code
- cache hit / miss

Each medication check should log:

- candidate input
- normalized candidate result
- normalized current meds
- evidence sources used
- finding types produced
- final status
- whether AI summary succeeded

Do not log:

- raw secrets
- full user identifiers if avoidable
- unredacted sensitive payloads in production-like environments

Recommended logging style:

- JSON logs
- one event per meaningful step
- stable field names

## 19. Security Rules

- keep all third-party API calls server-side
- never expose AI or FDA keys in Expo client code
- redact user identifiers from AI prompts unless required
- store source provenance for every finding
- keep prompts minimal and evidence-bound

## 20. Optional Vision / Scan Feature

If time allows, support medication or pill scanning from image using OpenAI vision.

This should be a separate component, not mixed into the core check flow.

Suggested flow:

1. user uploads image
2. backend sends image to vision model
3. model proposes medication candidates or pill imprint text
4. backend converts result into RxNav search terms
5. user confirms the selected medication
6. normal medication workflow continues

Important rule:

- image recognition should suggest candidates, not silently finalize them

## 21. Optional Chat / Voice Check-In

If there is extra time:

- support daily text check-ins
- support voice capture that turns into structured medication intents

This should reuse the same normalization and evidence pipeline.

Do not build a separate medication reasoning system for voice or chat.

## 22. Apify Policy

Apify is not part of the core architecture.

It may be used only for:

- optional content enrichment
- optional scraping of non-authoritative presentation pages

It must not be used as a primary medication safety source.

Primary sources must remain:

- RxNav / RxNorm for normalization
- openFDA for official label evidence
- DailyMed as label fallback

## 23. Recommended Build Order

### Phase 1: foundation

- set up backend framework
- set up Supabase
- add env handling
- add logger / trace utilities
- add external API clients with retries and timeouts

### Phase 2: medication normalization

- build RxNav search endpoint
- build normalization service
- store selected user medications

### Phase 3: evidence retrieval

- build openFDA retrieval
- parse label sections
- add DailyMed fallback
- persist evidence cache

### Phase 4: check orchestration

- build medication check agent
- implement finding classifier
