### Phase 5: AI summary

- add OpenAI summarizer
- constrain prompt to structured evidence
- return final hackathon-friendly output

### Phase 6: stretch goals

- image scanning
- chat / voice check-ins
- richer UI-facing explanation formats

## 24. Acceptance Criteria

The backend is successful when:

- user can search and add medications reliably
- user can check a new medication against existing medications
- every response includes source-backed rationale
- explicit openFDA interaction text is surfaced clearly when present
- incomplete evidence is clearly labeled as incomplete
- no endpoint returns a fake "safe to take" result
- logs are detailed enough to debug a failed demo in minutes

## 25. Final Recommendation

For the hackathon, keep the architecture simple:

- one backend
- one orchestration agent/service
- small components underneath
- Supabase for persistence and caching
- OpenAI only for grounded summarization
- strong logging everywhere

The winning version of this backend is not the most clinically ambitious one.

The winning version is the one that is:

- explainable
- reliable
- fast enough for demo use
- easy to debug live
- honest about uncertainty
